[1] Saint Barthelemy
Date: Wed 20 Feb 2008
Source: Ministere de la Sante, de la Jeunesse et des Sports, Point
Epidemiologique 2008(6) [in French, trans. & summ. Mod.TY]
<http://www.invs.sante.fr/presse/2008/le_point_sur/dengue_pep_st_barth_200208/PEP%20SBSM%202008-6_dengue.pdf>


Last week [11-17 Feb 2008] there was a further rise in the number of
clinically suspected [dengue] cases (estimated at 29) and biologically
[laboratory] confirmed cases (9).

Since the beginning of the pre-alert, it is estimated that about 340 people
consulted a GP (general practitioner) for a clinical syndrome suggestive of
dengue fever, and 4 adults who presented a serious form [of the disease]
were treated in hospital. Since mid-December [2007] no hospitalizations
have been recorded.

Since December [2007], the [dengue virus] serotype most often identified
has been DEN-1, but serotype DEN-2 also circulates.

--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[It is interesting to know which dengue virus serotypes are circulating in
these outbreaks. A map showing the location of the French overseas
collectivity of Saint Barthelemy in the Caribbean can be accessed at
<http://www.worldatlas.com/webimage/countrys/namerica/caribb/stbarts.htm>.
- Mod.TY]

******
[2] Saint Martin
Date: Wed 20 Feb 2008
Source: Ministere de la Sante, de la Jeunesse et des Sports, Point
Epidemiologique 2008(6) [in French, trans. & summ. Mod.TY]
<http://www.invs.sante.fr/presse/2008/le_point_sur/dengue_pep_st_barth_200208/PEP%20SBSM%202008-6_dengue.pdf>



The decrease in the number of clinically suspected [dengue] cases continued
over the past 3 consecutive weeks. The development of biologically
confirmed [laboratory] cases follows the same dynamic, but the 2 indicators
are still above the epidemic threshold.

Since the beginning of the epidemic (2nd week of November [2007]), an
estimated 1550 total of clinically suspected cases of dengue have been
reported. Over the same period, there have been 17 hospitalizations for
biologically [laboratory] confirmed cases, including 12 adults (9 with
serious disease) and 5 children (with only the classical form of the disease).

The predominant dengue virus serotype is DEN-1, but dengue viruses 2 and 4
are also circulating.

--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[A map showing the location of the French overseas collectivity of Saint
Martin in the Caribbean can be accessed at
<http://www.worldatlas.com/webimage/countrys/namerica/caribb/stmartin.htm>.
- Mod.TY]

