[3] Brazil: (Rio de Janeiro)
Date: Mon 18 Feb 2008
Source: O Globo Online [in Portuguese, trans. & summ. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://oglobo.globo.com/rio/mat/2008/02/18/rio_tem_um_caso_de_dengue_cada_15_minutos-425710690.asp>


The rain that fell on Rio this 2nd Thursday [18 Feb 2008] will aggravate
the dengue situation in the city. This disease, caused by [dengue virus
transmitted by] the bite of _Aedes aegypti_ is progressing rapidly. From
Thursday [14 Feb 2008] to Friday [15 Feb 2008] of last week 1110 new cases
were reported, a number higher than that registered in the whole month of
January 2007.

So far, more than 5000 people had dengue in 2008, according to the
Municipal Health Secretariat. This gives an average of one case every 15
minutes. The Secretariat also confirmed 3 deaths from dengue since January
[2008], and is investigating 12 other deaths.

--
communicated by:
ProMED-PORT
<promed@promedmail.org>

[A map of Brazil showing the states can be accessed at
<http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/americas/brazil.jpg>. - Mod.TY]

******
[4] Brazil: (Rondonia)
Date: Fri 22 Feb 2008
Source: Rondonoticias [in Portuguese, trans. & summ. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www.rondonoticias.com.br/showNew.jsp?CdMateria=71285&CdTpMateria=7>


The numbers of cases of dengue in the Capital [of Rondonia state] have
multiplied every day. Just in the health centers, about 70 per cent of
patients exhibit symptoms of the disease. However, this percentage does not
reflect reality, in that many patients do not seek medical care and so are
not recorded.

In the capital, as is common at this time of year due to the winter rainy
season in the Amazon, the number of cases increases. The municipal councils
do not take precautions to prevent an outbreak and only last year [2007],
Porto Velho reported more than 1400 [dengue] cases. Estimates of [dengue
cases] last year [2007] show that in many districts there was a real epidemic.

--
communicated by:
ProMED-PORT
<promed@promedmail.org>

******
[5] Brazil: (national)
Date: Fri 22 Feb 2008
Source: Folha Online [in Portuguese, trans. & summ. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www1.folha.uol.com.br/folha/cotidiano/ult95u375107.shtml>


The Ministry of Health communicated on Friday afternoon [22 Feb 2008] a 40
per cent decline in the number of dengue cases in the country recorded
during the 1st 5 weeks of 2008, in comparison with the same period last
year [2007]. There were 32 122 recorded cases of the disease this year
[2008], compared with 53 224 in the 1st 5 weeks of 2007.

Although the national average has a decline [in dengue cases], in some
states cases increased. The state of Rio [de Janeiro] had 117 per cent more
recorded cases of dengue than in last year [2007], as well as in comparison
with the 1st 5 weeks of this year [2008]. So far, 10 people have died of
DHF [dengue hemorrhagic fever] in Rio, of a total of 14 [DHF deaths] across
the country as registered by the ministry.

In the analysis by region, the only increase [in the number of cases]
occurred in the north: 54 per cent. The biggest drop was in the central
west of the country, with 81 per cent, followed by decreases of 27 per cent
in the north east, 26 per cent in the south, and 5 per cent in the south
east. In the State of Sao Paulo, there was a 95 per cent drop in dengue
cases in this same period, according to the totals. In Santa Catarina, no
local cases were registered, only [cases of] people who [were infected
elsewhere and] reached the state already infected with the disease [virus].
Without the increase in Rio, the fall of the national average would be 55
per cent, the ministry reported.

The governor of Rio, Sergio Cabral, said that the major [dengue infection]
indexes are concentrated in the city of Rio. He announced a series of
measures to try to lower the number of cases. Legislation was sent to the
Legislative Assembly of the State of Rio de Janeiro, [authorizing the
intervention of] public health officials in private and public buildings in
order to investigate possible outbreaks of dengue in the homes in the
state. According to the Ministry of Health, about 80 per cent of outbreaks
of the disease occur in household [residential? - Mod.SH] areas.

--
communicated by:
ProMED-PORT
<promed@promedmail.org>

******
[6] Palau
Date: Mon 25 Feb 2008
Source: Marianas Variety [edited]
<http://www.mvariety.com/?module=displaystory&story_id=7173&format=html>


The Bureau of Public Health has alerted the public that the number of
confirmed cases of dengue fever continues to increase. The bureau began
testing and confirming presented cases in May 2007. Except for July and
December 2007, the number of cases has been in the double-digit category
with February 2008 showing an exceptional increase -- 16 new cases in the
1st couple of weeks.

It is important for residents to clean and maintain their yards to
eliminate all actual and potential mosquito-breeding sites. This will
prevent the spreading of this disease in Palau. The public is also urged to
use insect repellant to prevent mosquito bites, including using long
sleeves, pants, socks, and shoes when cleaning around the house.

--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail rapporteur Brent Barrett

[A map of the Mariana Islands showing the location of the Palau Islands can
be accessed at <http://www.peacesat.hawaii.edu/40RESOURCES/Maps/palau.htm>.
- Mod.TY]

