[7] East Timor
Date: Mon 25 Feb 2008
From: Thomas Coombs <tigertom101@hotmail.com>


The wet season in Timor L'este [East Timor] has produced the predicable
wave of dengue fever in Dili. Our organization, providing health care to
Australian 'expat' workers, has had 20 confirmed dengue cases since the
start of 2008.

Of these, 13 cases were serotyped, demonstrating 12 cases [of dengue virus]
serotype 4 and one [dengue virus] serotype 1 by PCR [polymerase chain
reaction].

These cases are the tip of the iceberg in Dili but serve to demonstrate the
continued circulation of multiple dengue virus serotypes.

--
Dr Thomas Coombs MBBS BSc MPH
Aspen Medical
Dili
Timor L'este
<tigertom101@hotmail.com>

[ProMED-mail is especially appreciative of receiving 1st-hand reports of
outbreaks from the field and Dr Coombs is thanked for his timely report.

A map of East Timor can be accessed at
<http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/middle_east_and_asia/east_timor_pol_03.jpg>.
- Mod.TY]

******
[8] Malaysia
Date: Wed 20 Feb 2008
Source: Bernama (Malaysian National News Agency) [edited]
<http://www.bernama.com/bernama/v3/news.php?id=315091>


From 10-16 Feb [2008], 2 more deaths as a result of dengue were recorded
bringing the number of fatalities to 3 so far this year. The 1st fatality
happened in week 3 of January [2008]. The Health Ministry's diseases
control division director Datuk Dr Hasan Abdul Rahman said at total of 888
cases of dengue were reported nationwide between 10-16 Feb [2008], an
increase of 141 cases from the previous week.

"Almost all states recorded an increase in the number of cases during the
period (10-16 Feb [2008]) except for Perlis, Kedah, Johor, and Putrajaya,"
he said here on Wednesday [20 Feb 2008]. During the same period the owners
of 56 premises, mostly shops and houses, were fined a total of MYR 12 000
[USD 3733] after it was found the premises were breeding grounds for the
_Aedes_ mosquito, which is responsible for spreading the disease, he added.

--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail rapporteur Brent Barrett

[It would be interesting to know how effective fines are in getting
community compliance with elimination of dengue virus vector mosquito
breeding sites. One supposes that a vigorous public education campaign
would be necessary before imposing fines.

A map of Malaysia showing its administrative divisions can be accessed at
<http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/middle_east_and_asia/malaysia_adm98.jpg>. -
Mod.TY]

******
[9] Philippines: (Zamboanga City)
Date: Sat 23 Feb 2008
Source: GMA News.TV [edited]
<http://www.gmanews.tv/story/81894/Over-170-infected-with-dengue-virus-in-Zambo-City-mayor-says>


Over 170 people have been infected with the dengue virus in [Zamboanga
City] since early this year [2008], according to Mayor Celso Lobregat.
"There is an outbreak of dengue, according to the City Health Office, and
we are appealing to everybody to help us fight dengue by cleaning our
houses, backyards, and surroundings and to get rid of breeding places of
mosquitoes, such as stagnant water, canals, flower pots, and discarded
tires," he said in a television broadcast. He also appealed to village
officials to continue their cleanup drive to curtail the rise in dengue cases.

Lobregat said the dengue outbreak affected many villages. He said most of
the victims were children. The number of dengue cases from January to
February [2008] is 5 times more than the same period last year [2007],
according to Lobregat.

Last year [2007], the Department of Health (DoH) said more than 300 people
had died due to dengue, while 30 000 more were infected with the disease.

According to the DoH, the most effective way to fight dengue is to search
and destroy the breeding sites of _Aedes aegypti_ mosquitoes, such as
coconut husks and empty bottles and tin cans.

[byline: Al Jacinto]

--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail rapporteur Brent Barrett

[Zamboanga City is located on the far SW part of Mindanao Island. A map of
the area can be accessed at <http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zamboanga_City>.
- Mod.TY]
